# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: documentary-film
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Eastman Kodak introduced 16 mm film in 1923, as a less expensive alternative to 35 mm film for amateurs.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The same year the Victor Animatograph Corporation started producing their own 16 mm cameras and projectors.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] During the 1920s, the format was often referred to by the professional industry as 'sub-standard'.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Kodak hired Willard Beech Cook from his 28 mm Pathescope of America company to create the new 16 mm 'Kodascope Library'.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] In addition to making home movies, people could buy or rent films from the library, a key selling aspect of the format.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Intended for amateur use, 16 mm film was one of the first formats to use acetate safety film as a film base.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Kodak never used nitrate film for the format, owing to the high flammability of the nitrate base.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Kodak discontinued all nitrate base use in 1952.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The silent 16 mm format was initially aimed at the home enthusiast, but by the 1930s it had begun to make inroads into the educational market.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The addition of optical sound tracks and, most notably, Kodachrome in 1935, gave an enormous boost to its popularity.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The format was used extensively during World War II (*To the Shores of Iwo Jima*), and there was a huge expansion of 16 mm professional filmmaking in the post-war years.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Films for government, business, medical and industrial clients created a large network of 16 mm professional filmmakers and related service industries in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The advent of television production also enhanced the use of 16 mm film, initially for its advantage of cost and portability over 35 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] At first used as a news-gathering format, the 16 mm format was also used to create television programming shot outside the confines of the more rigid television studio production sets.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The home movie market gradually switched to the even less expensive 8 mm and Super 8 mm film formats.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] 16 mm, using light cameras, was extensively used for television production in many countries before portable video cameras appeared.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] In Britain, the BBC's Ealing-based film department made significant use of 16mm film and, during its peak, employed over 50 film crews.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Throughout much of the 1960s–1990s period, these crews made use of cameras such as the Arriflex ST and Eclair NPR in combination with quarter-inch sound recorders, such as the Nagra III.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Using these professional tools, film department crews would work on some of the most significant programmes produced by the BBC, including *Man Alive*, *Panorama* and *Chronicle*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Usually made up of five people, these small crews were able to work incredibly efficiently and, even in hostile environments, were able to film an entire programme with a shooting ratio of less than 5:1.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Beginning in the 1950s, news organizations and documentarians in the United States frequently shot on portable Auricon and, later, CP-16 cameras that were self-blimped and had the ability to record sound directly on film.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The introduction of magnetic striped film further improved sound fidelity.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Replacing analog video devices, digital video has made significant inroads in television production use.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Nevertheless, 16 mm is still in use in its Super 16 ratio (see below) for productions seeking its specific look.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Two perforation pitches are available for 16 mm film.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] One specification, known as "long pitch", has a spacing of 7.62 mm (0.300 in) and is used primarily for print and reversal film stocks.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Negative and intermediate film stocks have perforations spaced 7.605 mm (0.2994 in), known as "short pitch".
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] These differences allow for the sharpest and smoothest possible image when making prints using a contact printer.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Film stocks are available in either 'single-perf' or 'double-perf', meaning the film is perforated on either one or both edges.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The picture-taking area of standard 16 mm is 10.26 mm × 7.49 mm (0.404 in × 0.295 in), an aspect ratio of 1.37, the standard pre-widescreen Academy ratio for 35 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The "nominal" picture projection area (per SMPTE RP 20-2003) is 0.380 in by 0.284 in, and the maximum picture projection area (per SMPTE ST 233-2003) is 0.384 in by 0.286 in, each implying an aspect ratio of 1.34:1.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Double-perf 16 mm film, the original format, has a perforation at both sides of every frame line.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Single-perf is perforated at one side only, making room for an optical or magnetic soundtrack along the other side.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The variant called **Super 16 mm**, **Super 16**, or **16 mm Type W** is an adaptation of the 1.66 (1.66:1 or 15:9) aspect ratio of the "Paramount format" to 16 mm film.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] It was developed by Swedish cinematographer Rune Ericson in 1969, using single-sprocket film and taking advantage of the extra room for an expanded picture area of 12.52 mm × 7.41 mm (0.493 in × 0.292 in), giving an aspect ratio of 1.69.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] And, with the recent development of digital intermediate workflows, it is now possible to digitally enlarge to a 35 mm sound print with virtually no quality loss (given a high quality digital scan), or alternatively to use high-quality video equipment for the original image capture.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] In 2009, German lens manufacturer Vantage introduced a series of anamorphic lenses under its HAWK brand.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] These provided a 1.30x squeeze factor (as opposed to the standard 2×) specifically for the Super 16 format, allowing nearly all of the Super 16 frame to be used for 2.39:1 widescreen photography.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The DIY-crafted **Ultra 16** is a variation of Super 16.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] DeMarco is credited with inventing Ultra 16 in 1996 while shooting tests for Darren Aronofsky's *Pi*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Ultra 16 is created by widening the left and right sides of the gate of a standard 16 mm camera by 0.7 mm to expose part of the horizontal area between the perforations.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Perforation placement on standard 16 mm film at the divisions between frames accommodates use of these normally unexposed areas.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Thus, almost all standard 16 mm optics can now achieve the wider image in Ultra 16, but without the above pitfalls and optical "shortcomings" encountered when attempting their use for Super 16.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The only suppliers of 16 mm color reversal/negative film in 2022 were Kodak and Orwo.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Agfa and Fuji closed their film manufacturing facilities in the 2010s.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] B&W films are still produced by Kodak, Foma and ORWO/Filmotec, with ORWO/Filmotec having begun sales of a new color negative film in May of 2022.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] 16 mm film is used in television, such as for the *Hallmark Hall of Fame* anthology (it has since been produced in 16:9 high definition) and *Friday Night Lights* and *The O.C.* as well as *The Walking Dead* in the US.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] In the UK, the format is exceedingly popular for television series such as *Doc Martin*, dramas and commercials.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) played a large part in the development of the format.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] As of 2016, the format was frequently used for student films, while its use in documentaries had almost disappeared.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] With the advent of HDTV, Super 16 film is still used for some productions destined for HD.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Some low-budget theatrical features are shot on 16 mm and super 16 mm such as Kevin Smith's 16 mm 1994 independent hit *Clerks,* or *Man Bites Dog*, *Mid90s* and *Closer to Home*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Thanks to advances in film stock and digital technology—specifically digital intermediate (DI)—the format has dramatically improved in picture quality since the 1970s, and is now a revitalized option.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] *Vera Drake*, for example, was shot on Super 16 mm film, digitally scanned at a high resolution, edited and color graded, and then printed out onto 35 mm film via a laser film recorder.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Because of the digital process, the final 35 mm print quality is good enough to fool some professionals into thinking it was shot on 35 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] In Britain, most exterior television footage was shot on 16 mm from the 1960s until the 1990s, when the development of more portable television cameras and videotape machines led to video replacing 16 mm in many instances.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Many drama shows and documentaries were made entirely on 16 mm, notably *Brideshead Revisited*, *The Jewel in the Crown*, *The Ascent of Man*, *Life on Earth*, and the early seasons of *Poirot*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] More recently, the advent of widescreen television has led to the use of *Super* 16.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] For example, the 2008 BBC fantasy drama series *Merlin* was shot in Super 16.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] As recently as 2010, *Scrubs* was shot on Super16 and aired either as 4:3 SD (first 7 seasons) or as 16:9 HD (seasons 8 and 9).
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] John Inwood, the cinematographer of the series, believed that footage from his Aaton XTR Prod camera was not only sufficient to air in high definition, it "looked terrific".
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The Academy Award winning *Leaving Las Vegas* was shot on 16 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The first two seasons of *Buffy the Vampire Slayer* were shot on 16 mm and switched to 35 mm for its later seasons.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The first season of *Sex and the City* was shot on 16 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] All three seasons of *Veronica Mars* were shot on 16 mm and aired in HD.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] *This Is Spinal Tap*, and Christopher Guest's subsequent mockumentary films, are shot in Super 16 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The first three seasons of *Stargate SG-1* (bar the season 3 finale and the effects shots) were shot in 16 mm, before switching to 35 mm for later seasons.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Peter Jackson's 1992 zombie comedy *Braindead* was shot on Super 16mm, so that more of its $3 million budget could be spent on its extensive gore effects.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Catherine Hardwicke's 2003 teen drama *Thirteen* was shot on Super 16mm, due to low budget of $2 million.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The 2009 Academy Award winner for Best Picture, *The Hurt Locker*, was shot using Aaton Super 16 mm cameras and Fujifilm 16 mm film stocks.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The cost savings over 35 mm allowed the production to utilize multiple cameras for many shots, exposing over one million feet of film.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] British Napoleonic-era TV drama *Sharpe* was shot on Super 16 mm right through to the film *Sharpe's Challenge*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] For the last film in the series, *Sharpe's Peril*, the producers switched to 35 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Darren Aronofsky shot *mother!* on 16 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Linus Sandgren shot most of the 2018 biographical drama *First Man* on Super 16.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Spike Lee shot the Netflix film *Da 5 Bloods*' flashback scenes on 16 mm film, which was part of the reason cinematographer Newton Thomas Sigel was considered for an Oscar nomination.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] *The Insider* reports that Netflix was "initially concerned about having the movie's flashback scenes shot on grainy 16 mm film ...
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] There was pushback because it opened up a lot of challenges." According to Sigel, the film stock Lee wanted to use was expensive because it is rarely used.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] It would be even more expensive to shoot on 16mm film while on location in Vietnam and then ship the film back to the United States to be processed at a film lab.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Cornish filmmaker Mark Jenkin is notable for using 16 mm film and a hand-cranked 1978 Bolex camera, most notably in his films *Bait* and *Enys Men*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] 16mm film was also used to produce early Full-Motion Video arcade games, such as Nintendo's *Wild Gunman* (1974) and Kasco's *The Driver* (1979).
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Independent filmmaking - Many modern creatives utilise the 16mm format in smaller independent productions such as music videos, short films and advertising.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] A number of digital cameras approximate the look of the 16 mm format by using 16 mm-sized sensors and taking 16 mm lenses.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] These cameras include the Ikonoskop A-Cam DII (2008) and the Digital Bolex (2012).
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The Blackmagic Pocket Cinema Camera (2013) and the Blackmagic Micro Cinema Camera (2015) has a Super 16-sized sensor.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The Z CAM E2G (2019) even offers Digital 16 mm in 4K and with a global shutter.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The professional industry tends to use 16 mm cameras from Aaton and Arri, most notably the Aaton Xtera, Aaton XTRprod, Arriflex 16SR3, and Arriflex 416.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Aaton also released the A-Minima, which is about the size of a video camcorder and is used for specialized filming requiring smaller, more versatile cameras.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Photo Sonics have special extremely high speed cameras for 16 mm that film at up to 1,000 frames per second.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Panavision has produced the Panaflex 16, nicknamed "Elaine".
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] For amateur, hobbyist, and student use, it is more economical to use older models from Arri, Aaton, Auricon, Beaulieu, Bell and Howell, Bolex, Canon, Cinema Products, Eclair, Keystone, Krasnogorsk, Mitchell, and others.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Most original movie production companies that use film shoot on 35 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The 35 mm size must be converted or reduced to 16 mm for 16 mm systems.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] There are multiple ways of obtaining a 16 mm print from 35 mm.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The preferred method is to strike a 16 mm negative from the original 35 mm negative and then make a print from the new 16 mm negative.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] A 16 mm negative struck from the original 35 mm negative is called an *original*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] A new 16 mm print made from a print with no negative is called a *reversal*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Film traders often refer to 16 mm prints by the print's production method, i.e., an *original*, *reversal*, *dupe down*, *double dupe*, or *double dupe down*.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Over time, the cyan, magenta and yellow dyes that form the image in color 16 mm film inevitably fade.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The rate of deterioration depends on storage conditions and the film type.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] In the case of Kodachrome amateur and documentary films and Technicolor IB (imbibition process) color prints, the dyes are so stable and the deterioration so slow that even prints now over 70 years old typically show no obvious problems.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Dyes in the far more common Eastmancolor print film and similar products from other manufacturers are notoriously unstable.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] Prior to the introduction of a longer-lasting "low fade" type in 1979, Eastmancolor prints routinely suffered from easily seen color shift and fading within ten years.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] The dyes degrade at different rates, with magenta being the longest-lasting, eventually resulting in a pale reddish image with little if any other color discernible.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] In the process of digitizing old color films, even badly faded source material can sometimes be restored to full color through digital techniques that amplify the faded dye colors.
[src:documentary-film/16-mm-film] A digital intermediate scanned from the original negative (if it was processed and stored correctly) can often fully restore colors.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The basic components of 3D film were introduced separately between 1833 and 1839.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Stroboscopic animation was developed by Joseph Plateau in 1832 and published in 1833 in the form of a stroboscopic disc, which he later called the fantascope and became better known as the phénakisticope.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Around the very same time (1832/1833), Charles Wheatstone developed the stereoscope, but he did not really make it public before June 1838.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The first practical forms of photography were introduced in January 1839 by Louis Daguerre and Henry Fox Talbot.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] A combination of these elements into animated stereoscopic photography may have been conceived early on, but for decades it did not become possible to capture motion in real-time photographic recordings due to the long exposure times necessary for the light-sensitive emulsions that were used.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Charles Wheatstone got inventor Henry Fox Talbot to produce some calotype pairs for the stereoscope and received the first results in October 1840.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Only a few more experimental stereoscopic photographs were made before David Brewster introduced his stereoscope with lenses in 1849.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Wheatstone also approached Joseph Plateau with the suggestion to combine the stereoscope with the fantascope.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1849, Plateau published about this concept in an article about several improvements made to his fantascope and suggested a stop-motion technique that would involve a series of photographs of purpose-made plaster statuettes in different poses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The idea reached Jules Duboscq, an instrument maker who already marketed Plateau's Fantascope as well as the stereoscopes of Wheatstone and Brewster.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In November 1852, Duboscq added the concept of his "Stéréoscope-fantascope, ou Bïoscope" to his stereoscope patent.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Production of images proved very difficult, since the photographic sequence had to be carefully constructed from separate still images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The bioscope was no success, and the only extant disc, without apparatus, is found in the Joseph Plateau collection of the University of Ghent.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The disc contains 12 albumen image pairs of a machine in motion.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Most other early attempts to create motion pictures also aimed to include stereoscopic effects.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In November 1851, Antoine Claudet claimed to have created a stereoscope that showed people in motion.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The device initially only showed two phases, but during the next two years, Claudet worked on a camera that would record stereoscopic pairs for four different poses (patented in 1853).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Claudet found that the stereoscopic effect did not work properly in this device, but believed the illusion of motion was successful.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1855, Johann Nepomuk Czermak published an article about his Stereophoroskop.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] His first idea to create 3D animation involved sticking pins in a stroboscopic disc to create a sequence that would show one pin moving further into the cardboard and back.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] He also designed a device that would feed the image pairs from two stroboscopic discs into one lenticular stereoscope and a vertical predecessor of the zoetrope.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] On February 27, 1860, Peter Hubert Desvignes received British patent no.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] 537 for 28 monocular and stereoscopic variations of cylindrical stroboscopic devices.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] This included a version that used an endless band of pictures running between two spools that was intermittently lit by an electric spark.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Desvignes' *Mimoscope*, received an Honourable Mention "for ingenuity of construction" at the 1862 International Exhibition in London.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1861, American engineer Coleman Sellers II received US patent No.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] 35,317 for the kinematoscope, a device that exhibited "stereoscopic pictures as to make them represent objects in motion".
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In his application he stated: "This has frequently been done with plane pictures but has never been, with stereoscopic pictures".
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] He used three sets of stereoscopic photographs in a sequence with some duplicates to regulate the flow of a simple repetitive motion, but also described a system for very large series of pictures of complicated motion.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] On August 11, 1877, the *Daily Alta* newspaper announced a project by Eadward Muybridge and Leland Stanford to produce sequences of photographs of a running horse with 12 stereoscopic cameras.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Muybridge had much experience with stereo photography and had already made instantaneous pictures of Stanford's horse Occident running at full speed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] He eventually managed to shoot the proposed sequences of running horses in June 1878 with stereoscopic cameras.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Thomas Edison demonstrated his phonograph on November 29, 1877, after previous announcements of the device for recording and replaying sound had been published earlier in the year.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] An article in *Scientific American* concluded, "It is already possible, by ingenious optical contrivances, to throw stereoscopic photographs of people on screens in full view of an audience.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Add the talking phonograph to counterfeit their voices, and it would be difficult to carry the illusion of real presence much further".
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Wordsworth Donisthorpe announced in the January 24, 1878, edition of *Nature* that he would advance that conception: "By combining the phonograph with the kinesigraph, I will undertake not only to produce a talking picture of Mr.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Gladstone, which, with motionless lips and unchanged expression, shall positively recite his latest anti-Turkish speech in his own voice and tone.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Not only this, but the life size photograph itself shall move and gesticulate precisely as he did when making the speech, the words and gestures corresponding as in real life." Dr.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Phipson, a correspondent for British news in a French photography magazine, relayed the concept but renamed the device "Kinétiscope" to reflect the viewing purpose rather than the recording option.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] This was picked up in the United States and discussed in an interview with Edison later in the year.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Neither Donisthorpe's nor Edison's later moving picture results were stereoscopic.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In the late 1890s, British film pioneer William Friese-Greene filed a patent for a 3D film process.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In his patent, two films were projected side by side on screen.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The viewer looked through a stereoscope to converge the two images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Because of the obtrusive mechanics behind this method, theatrical use was not practical.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Frederic Eugene Ives patented his stereo camera rig in 1900.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The camera had two lenses positioned 1+3⁄4 inches (4.45 centimeters) apart.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Waddell presented tests to an audience at the Astor Theater in New York City.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] However, according to Adolph Zukor in his 1953 autobiography *The Public Is Never Wrong: My 50 Years in the Motion Picture Industry*, nothing was produced in this process after these tests.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] By 1909, the German film market suffered much from overproduction and too much competition.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] German film tycoon Oskar Messter had initially gained much financial success with the Tonbild synchronized sound films of his Biophon system since 1903, but the films were losing money by the end of the decade, and Messter would stop Tonbild production in 1913.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Producers and exhibitors were looking into new film attractions and invested for instance in colorful imagery.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The development of stereoscopic cinema seemed a logical step to lure visitors back into the movie theaters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1909, German civil engineer August Engelsmann patented a process that projected filmed performances within a physical decor on an actual stage.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Soon after, Messter obtained patents for a very similar process, probably by agreement with Engelsmann, and started marketing it as "Alabastra".
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Performers were brightly dressed and brightly lit while filmed against a black background, mostly miming their singing or musical skills or dancing to the circa four-minute pre-recorded phonographs.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The film recordings would be projected from below, to appear as circa 30 inch figures on a glass pane in front of a small stage, in a setup very similar to the Pepper's ghost illusion that offered a popular stage trick technique since the 1860s.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The glass pane was not visible to the audience and the projected figures seemed able to move around freely across the stage in their virtual tangible and lifelike appearance.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The brightness of the figures was necessary to avoid see-through spots and made them resemble alabaster sculptures.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] To adapt to this appearance, several films featured Pierrot or other white clowns, while some films were probably hand-coloured.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Although Alabastra was well received by the press, Messter produced few titles, hardly promoted them and abandoned it altogether a few years later.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] He believed the system to be uneconomical due to its need for special theatres instead of the widely available movie screens, and he did not like that it seemed only suitable for stage productions and not for "natural" films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Nonetheless, there were numerous imitators in Germany and Messter and Engelsmann still teamed with American businessman Frank Joseph Godsol (Goldsoll) set up a short-lived variant named "Fantomo" in 1914.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Rather in agreement with Messter or not, Karl Juhasz and Franz Haushofer opened a Kinoplastikon theatre in Vienna in 1911.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Their patented system was very similar to Alabaster, but projected life-size figures from the wings of the stage.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] With much higher ticket prices than standard cinema, it was targeted at middle-class audiences to fill the gap between low-brow films and high-class theatre.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Audiences reacted enthusiastically and by 1913 there reportedly were 250 theatres outside Austria, in France, Italy, United Kingdom, Russia and North America.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] However, the first Kinoplastikon in Paris started in January 1914 and the premiere in New York took place in the Hippodrome in March 1915.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Kinoplastikon, presumably in collaboration with Cecil Hepworth.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Theodore Brown, the licensee in the U.K. also patented a variant with front and back projection and reflected decor, and Goldsoll applied for a very similar patent only 10 days later.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Further development and exploitation was probably halted by World War I.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Alabastra and Kinoplastikon were often advertised as stereoscopic and screenless.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Eventually, longer (multi-reel) films with story arcs proved to be the way out of the crisis in the movie market and supplanted the previously popular short films that mostly aimed to amuse people with tricks, gags or other brief variety and novelty attractions.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Sound film, stereoscopic film and other novel techniques were relatively cumbersome to combine with multiple reels and were abandoned for a while.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The earliest confirmed 3D film shown to an out-of-house audience was *The Power of Love*, which premiered at the Ambassador Hotel Theater in Los Angeles on September 27, 1922.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The camera rig was a product of the film's producer, Harry K.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] It was filmed dual-strip in black and white, and single strip color anaglyphic release prints were produced using a color film invented and patented by Harry K.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] A single projector could be used to display the movie but anaglyph glasses were used for viewing.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The camera system and special color release print film all received U.S Patent No.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] After a preview for exhibitors and press in New York City, the film dropped out of sight, apparently not booked by exhibitors, and is now considered lost.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Early in December 1922, William Van Doren Kelley, inventor of the Prizma color system, cashed in on the growing interest in 3D films started by Fairall's demonstration and shot footage with a camera system of his own design.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Kelley then struck a deal with Samuel "Roxy" Rothafel to premiere the first in his series of "Plasticon" shorts entitled *Movies of the Future* at the Rivoli Theater in New York City.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Also in December 1922, Laurens Hammond (later inventor of the Hammond organ) premiered his Teleview system, which had been shown to the trade and press in October.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Teleview was the first alternating-frame 3D system seen by the public.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Using left-eye and right-eye prints and two interlocked projectors, left and right frames were alternately projected, each pair being shown three times to suppress flicker.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Viewing devices attached to the armrests of the theater seats had rotary shutters that operated synchronously with the projector shutters, producing a clean and clear stereoscopic result.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The only theater known to have installed Teleview was the Selwyn Theater in New York City, and only one show was ever presented with it: a group of short films, an exhibition of live 3D shadows, and *M.A.R.S.*, the only Teleview feature.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The show ran for several weeks, apparently doing good business as a novelty (*M.A.R.S.* itself got poor reviews), but Teleview was never seen again.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1922, Frederic Eugene Ives and Jacob Leventhal began releasing their first stereoscopic shorts made over a three-year period.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The first film, entitled *Plastigrams*, was distributed nationally by Educational Pictures in the red-and-blue anaglyph format.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Ives and Leventhal then went on to produce the following stereoscopic shorts in the "Stereoscopiks Series" released by Pathé Films in 1925: *Zowie* (April 10), *Luna-cy!* (May 18), *The Run-Away Taxi* (December 17) and *Ouch* (December 17).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] On September 22, 1924, *Luna-cy!* was re-released in the De Forest Phonofilm sound-on-film system.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The late 1920s to early 1930s saw little interest in stereoscopic pictures.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In Paris, Louis Lumiere shot footage with his stereoscopic camera in September 1933.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The following March he exhibited a remake of his 1895 short film *L'Arrivée du Train*, this time in anaglyphic 3D, at a meeting of the French Academy of Science.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1936, Leventhal and John Norling were hired based on their test footage to film MGM's *Audioscopiks* series.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The prints were by Technicolor in the red-and-green anaglyph format, and were narrated by Pete Smith.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The first film, *Audioscopiks*, premiered January 11, 1936, and *The New Audioscopiks* premiered January 15, 1938.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] *Audioscopiks* was nominated for the Academy Award in the category Best Short Subject, Novelty in 1936.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] With the success of the two Audioscopiks films, MGM produced one more short in anaglyph 3D, another Pete Smith Specialty called *Third Dimensional Murder* (1941).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Unlike its predecessors, this short was shot with a studio-built camera rig.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Prints were by Technicolor in red-and-blue anaglyph.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The short is notable for being one of the few live-action appearances of the Frankenstein Monster as conceived by Jack Pierce for Universal Studios outside of their company.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] While many of these films were printed by color systems, none of them was actually in color, and the use of the color printing was only to achieve an anaglyph effect.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] While attending Harvard University, Edwin H.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Land conceived the idea of reducing glare by polarizing light.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] He took a leave of absence from Harvard to set up a lab and by 1929 had invented and patented a polarizing sheet.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1932, he introduced **Polaroid J Sheet** as a commercial product.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] While his original intention was to create a filter for reducing glare from car headlights, Land did not underestimate the utility of his newly dubbed Polaroid filters in stereoscopic presentations.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In February 1936, Land gave the first public demonstration of Polaroid filters in conjunction with 3D photography at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The reaction was enthusiastic, and Land followed it up with an installation at the New York Museum of Science.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] It is unknown what film was run for audiences at this exhibition.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Using Polaroid filters meant an entirely new form of projection, however.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Two prints, each carrying either the right or left eye view, had to be synced up in projection using an external selsyn motor.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Furthermore, polarized light would be largely depolarized by a matte white screen, and only a silver screen or screen made of other reflective material would correctly reflect the separate images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Later that year, the feature, *Nozze Vagabonde* appeared in Italy, followed in Germany by *Zum Greifen nah* (*You Can Nearly Touch It*), and again in 1939 with Germany's *Sechs Mädel rollen ins Wochenend* (*Six Girls Drive Into the Weekend*).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The Italian film was made with the Gualtierotti camera; the two German productions with the Zeiss camera and the Vierling shooting system.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] All of these films were the first exhibited using Polaroid filters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The Zeiss Company in Germany manufactured glasses on a commercial basis commencing in 1936; they were also independently made around the same time in Germany by E.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1939, John Norling shot *In Tune With Tomorrow*, the first commercial 3D film using Polaroid in the US.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] This short premiered at the 1939 New York World's Fair and was created specifically for the Chrysler Motors Pavilion.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In it, a full 1939 Chrysler Plymouth is magically put together, set to music.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Originally in black and white, the film was so popular that it was re-shot in color for the following year at the fair, under the title *New Dimensions*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In 1953, it was reissued by RKO as *Motor Rhythm*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Another early short that utilized the Polaroid 3D process was 1940's *Magic Movies: Thrills For You* produced by the Pennsylvania Railroad Co. for the Golden Gate International Exposition.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Produced by John Norling, it was filmed by Jacob Leventhal using his own rig.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] It consisted of shots of various views that could be seen from the Pennsylvania Railroad's trains.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] In the 1940s, World War II prioritized military applications of stereoscopic photography and it once again went on the back burner in most producers' minds.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] What aficionados consider the "golden era" of 3D began in late 1952 with the release of the first color stereoscopic feature, *Bwana Devil*, produced, written and directed by Arch Oboler.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The film was shot in "Natural Vision", a process that was co-created and controlled by M.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Gunzberg, who built the rig with his brother Julian, Friend Baker and Lothrop Worth, shopped it without success to various studios before Oboler used it for this feature, which went into production with the title, *The Lions of Gulu*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The critically panned film was nevertheless highly successful with audiences due to the novelty of 3D, which increased Hollywood interest in 3D during a period that had seen declining box-office admissions.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] As with practically all of the features made during this boom, *Bwana Devil* was projected dual-strip, with Polaroid filters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] During the 1950s, the familiar disposable anaglyph glasses made of cardboard were mainly used for comic books, two shorts by exploitation specialist Dan Sonney, and three shorts produced by Lippert Productions.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] However, even the Lippert shorts were available in the dual-strip format alternatively.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Because the features utilized two projectors, the capacity limit of film being loaded onto each projector (about 6,000 feet (1,800 m), or an hour's worth of film) meant that an intermission was necessary for every feature-length film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Quite often, intermission points were written into the script at a major plot point.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] During Christmas of 1952, producer Sol Lesser quickly premiered the dual-strip showcase called *Stereo Techniques* in Chicago.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Lesser acquired the rights to five dual-strip shorts.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Two of them, *Now is the Time (to Put On Your Glasses)* and *Around is Around*, were directed by Norman McLaren in 1951 for the National Film Board of Canada.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The other three films were produced in Britain for The Festival of Britain in 1951 by Raymond Spottiswoode.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] These were *A Solid Explanation*, *Royal River*, and *The Black Swan*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] James Mage was also an early pioneer in the 3D craze.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Using his 16 mm 3D Bolex system, he premiered his *Triorama* program on February 10, 1953, with his four shorts: *Sunday In Stereo*, *Indian Summer*, *American Life*, and *This is Bolex Stereo*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Another early 3D film during the boom was the Lippert Productions short *A Day in the Country*, narrated by Joe Besser, which was composed mostly of test footage.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Unlike all of the other Lippert shorts, which were available in both dual-strip and anaglyph, this production was released in anaglyph only.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] April 1953 saw two groundbreaking features in 3D: Columbia's *Man in the Dark* and Warner Bros.' *House of Wax*, the first 3D feature with stereophonic sound.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The success of these two films proved that major studios now had a method of getting filmgoers back into theaters and away from television sets, which were causing a steady decline in attendance.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Universal-International released its first 3D feature, *It Came from Outer Space*, on May 27, 1953, with stereophonic sound.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] That was followed by Paramount's first 3D feature, *Sangaree* with Fernando Lamas and Arlene Dahl.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The Walt Disney Studios entered 3D with its May 28, 1953, release of *Melody*, which accompanied the first 3D western, Columbia's *Fort Ti* at its Los Angeles opening.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] It was later shown at Disneyland's Fantasyland Theater in 1957 as part of a program with Disney's other short *Working for Peanuts*, entitled, *3-D Jamboree*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The show was hosted by the Mousketeers and was in color.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Columbia released several 3D westerns produced by Sam Katzman and directed by William Castle.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Castle would later specialize in various technical in-theater gimmicks for such Columbia and Allied Artists features as *13 Ghosts*, *House on Haunted Hill*, and *The Tingler*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Columbia also produced the only slapstick comedies conceived for 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The Three Stooges starred in *Spooks* and *Pardon My Backfire*; dialect comic Harry Mimmo starred in *Down the Hatch*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Producer Jules White was optimistic about the possibilities of 3D as applied to slapstick (with pies and other projectiles aimed at the audience), but only two of his stereoscopic shorts were shown in 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] *Down the Hatch* was released as a conventional, "flat" motion picture.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] John Ireland, Joanne Dru and Macdonald Carey starred in the Jack Broder color production *Hannah Lee*, which premiered on June 19, 1953.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The film was directed by Ireland, who sued Broder for his salary.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Broder counter-sued, claiming that Ireland went over production costs with the film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Another famous entry in the golden era of 3D was the 3 Dimensional Pictures production of *Robot Monster*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The film was allegedly scribed in an hour by screenwriter Wyott Ordung and filmed in a period of two weeks on a shoestring budget.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Despite these shortcomings and the fact that the crew had no previous experience with the newly built camera rig, luck was on the cinematographer's side, as many find the 3D photography in the film is well shot and aligned.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] *Robot Monster* also has a notable score by then up-and-coming composer Elmer Bernstein.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The film was released June 24, 1953, and went out with the short *Stardust in Your Eyes*, which starred nightclub comedian, Slick Slavin.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] 20th Century Fox produced its only 3D feature, *Inferno*, in 1953, starring Rhonda Fleming.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Fleming, who also starred in *Those Redheads From Seattle*, and *Jivaro*, shares the spot for being the actress to appear in the most 3D features with Patricia Medina, who starred in *Sangaree*, *Phantom of the Rue Morgue* and *Drums of Tahiti*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] Zanuck expressed little interest in stereoscopic systems, and at that point was preparing to premiere the new widescreen film system, CinemaScope.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p01] The first decline in the theatrical 3D craze started in August and September 1953.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Sol Lesser attempted to follow up *Stereo Techniques* with a new showcase, this time five shorts that he himself produced.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The project was to be called *The 3-D Follies* and was to be distributed by RKO.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Unfortunately, because of financial difficulties and the general loss of interest in 3D, Lesser canceled the project during the summer of 1953, making it the first 3D film to be aborted in production.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Two of the three shorts were shot: *Carmenesque*, a burlesque number starring exotic dancer Lili St.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Cyr, and *Fun in the Sun*, a sports short directed by famed set designer/director William Cameron Menzies, who also directed the 3D feature *The Maze* for Allied Artists.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Although it was more expensive to install, the major competing realism process was wide-screen, but two-dimensional, anamorphic, first utilized by Fox with CinemaScope and its September premiere in *The Robe*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Anamorphic films needed only a single print, so synchronization was not an issue.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Cinerama was also a competitor from the start and had better quality control than 3D because it was owned by one company that focused on quality control.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] However, most of the 3D features past the summer of 1953 were released in the flat widescreen formats ranging from 1.66:1 to 1.85:1.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In early studio advertisements and articles about widescreen and 3D formats, widescreen systems were referred to as "3D", causing some confusion among scholars.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] There was no single instance of combining CinemaScope with 3D until 1960, with a film called *September Storm*, and even then, that was a blow-up from a non-anamorphic negative.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *September Storm* also went out with the last dual-strip short, *Space Attack*, which was actually shot in 1954 under the title *The Adventures of Sam Space*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In December 1953, 3D made a comeback with the release of several important 3D films, including MGM's musical *Kiss Me, Kate*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Kate* was the hill over which 3D had to pass to survive.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] MGM tested it in six theaters: three in 3D and three-flat.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] According to trade ads of the time, the 3D version was so well-received that the film quickly went into a wide stereoscopic release.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] However, most publications, including Kenneth Macgowan's classic film reference book *Behind the Screen*, state that the film did much better as a "regular" release.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The film, adapted from the popular Cole Porter Broadway musical, starred the MGM songbird team of Howard Keel and Kathryn Grayson as the leads, supported by Ann Miller, Keenan Wynn, Bobby Van, James Whitmore, Kurt Kasznar and Tommy Rall.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The film also prominently promoted its use of stereophonic sound.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Several other features that helped put 3D back on the map that month were the John Wayne feature *Hondo* (distributed by Warner Bros.), Columbia's *Miss Sadie Thompson* with Rita Hayworth, and Paramount's *Money From Home* with Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Paramount also released the cartoon shorts *Boo Moon* with Casper, the Friendly Ghost and *Popeye, Ace of Space* with Popeye the Sailor.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Paramount Pictures released a 3D Korean War film *Cease Fire* filmed on actual Korean locations in 1953.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] A string of successful films filmed in 3D followed the second wave, but many were widely or exclusively shown flat.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] 3D's final decline was in the late spring of 1954, for the same reasons as the previous lull, as well as the further success of widescreen formats with theater operators.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Even though Polaroid had created a well-designed "Tell-Tale Filter Kit" for the purpose of recognizing and adjusting out of sync and phase 3D, exhibitors still felt uncomfortable with the system and turned their focus instead to processes such as CinemaScope.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The last 3D feature to be released in that format during the "Golden era" was *Revenge of the Creature*, on February 23, 1955.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Ironically, the film had a wide release in 3D and was well received at the box office.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Stereoscopic films largely remained dormant for the first part of the 1960s, with those that were released usually being anaglyph exploitation films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] One film of notoriety was the Beaver-Champion/Warner Bros. production, *The Mask* (1961).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The film was shot in 2-D, but to enhance the bizarre qualities of the dream-world that is induced when the main character puts on a cursed tribal mask, these scenes went to anaglyph 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] These scenes were printed by Technicolor on their first run in red/green anaglyph.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Although 3D films appeared sparsely during the early 1960s, the true second wave of 3D cinema was set into motion by Arch Oboler, the producer who had started the craze of the 1950s.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Using a new technology called *Space-Vision 3D*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The origin of "Space-Vision 3D" goes back to Colonel Robert Vincent Bernier, a forgotten innovator in the history of stereoscopic motion pictures.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] His Trioptiscope Space-Vision lens was the gold standard for the production and exhibition of 3-D films for nearly 30 years.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] "Space-Vision 3D" stereoscopic films were printed with two images, one above the other, in a single academy ratio frame, on a single strip, and needed only one projector fitted with a special lens.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This so-called "over and under" technique eliminated the need for dual projector set-ups, and produced widescreen, but darker, less vivid, polarized 3D images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Unlike earlier dual system, it could stay in perfect synchronization, unless improperly spliced in repair.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Arch Oboler once again had the vision for the system that no one else would touch, and put it to use on his film entitled *The Bubble*, which starred Michael Cole, Deborah Walley, and Johnny Desmond.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] As with *Bwana Devil*, the critics panned *The Bubble*, but audiences flocked to see it, and it became financially sound enough to promote the use of the system to other studios, particularly independents, who did not have the money for expensive dual-strip prints of their productions.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 1970, Stereovision, a new entity founded by director/inventor Allan Silliphant and optical designer Chris Condon, developed a different 35 mm single-strip format, which printed two images squeezed side by side and used an anamorphic lens to widen the pictures through Polaroid filters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Sher (Sherpix) and Stereovision released the softcore sex comedy *The Stewardesses* (self-rated X, but later re-rated R by the MPAA).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Some 36 films worldwide were made with Stereovision over 25 years, using either a widescreen (above-below), anamorphic (side by side) or 70 mm 3D formats.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 2009 *The Stewardesses* was remastered by Chris Condon and director Ed Meyer, releasing it in XpanD 3D, RealD 3D and Dolby 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The quality of the 1970s 3D films was not much more inventive, as many were either softcore and even hardcore adult films, horror films, or a combination of both.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Paul Morrisey's *Flesh For Frankenstein* (aka *Andy Warhol's Frankenstein*) was a superlative example of such a combination.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Between 1981 and 1983 there was a new Hollywood 3D craze started by the spaghetti western *Comin' at Ya!*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] When *Parasite* was released it was billed as the first horror film to come out in 3D in over 20 years.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Horror films and reissues of 1950s 3D classics (such as Hitchcock's *Dial M for Murder*) dominated the 3D releases that followed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The second sequel in the *Friday the 13th* series, *Friday the 13th Part III*, was released very successfully.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Apparently saying "part 3 in 3D" was considered too cumbersome so it was shortened in the titles of *Jaws 3-D* and *Amityville 3-D*, which emphasized the screen effects to the point of being annoying at times, especially when flashlights were shone into the eyes of the audience.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The science fiction film *Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone* was the most expensive 3D film made up to that point with production costs about the same as *Star Wars* but not nearly the same box office success, causing the craze to fade quickly through spring 1983.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Other sci-fi/fantasy films were released as well including *Metalstorm: The Destruction of Jared-Syn* and *Treasure of the Four Crowns*, which was widely criticized for poor editing and plot holes, but did feature some truly spectacular closeups.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] 3D releases after the second craze included *The Man Who Wasn't There* (1983), *Silent Madness* and the 1985 animated film *Starchaser: The Legend of Orin*, whose plot seemed to borrow heavily from *Star Wars*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Only *Comin' At Ya!*, *Parasite*, and *Friday the 13th Part III* have been officially released on VHS and/or DVD in 3D in the United States (although *Amityville 3D* has seen a 3D DVD release in the United Kingdom).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Most of the 1980s 3D films and some of the classic 1950s films such as *House of Wax* were released on the now defunct Video Disc (VHD) format in Japan as part of a system that used shutter glasses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Most of these have been unofficially transferred to DVD and are available on the grey market through sites such as eBay.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Stereoscopic movies were also popular in other parts of the world, such as My Dear Kuttichathan, a Malayalam film which was shot with stereoscopic 3D and released in 1984.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the mid-1980s, IMAX began producing non-fiction films for its nascent 3D business, starting with *We Are Born of Stars* (Roman Kroitor, 1985).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] A key point was that this production, as with all subsequent IMAX productions, emphasized mathematical correctness of the 3D rendition and thus largely eliminated the eye fatigue and pain that resulted from the approximate geometries of previous 3D incarnations.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In addition, and in contrast to previous 35mm-based 3D presentations, the very large field of view provided by IMAX allowed a much broader 3D "stage", arguably as important in 3D film as it is theatre.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The Walt Disney Company also began more prominent use of 3D films in special venues to impress audiences with Magic Journeys (1982) and *Captain EO* (Francis Ford Coppola, 1986, starring Michael Jackson) being notable examples.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the same year, the National Film Board of Canada production *Transitions* (Colin Low), created for Expo 86 in Vancouver, was the first IMAX presentation using polarized glasses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Echoes of the Sun* (Roman Kroitor, 1990) was the first IMAX film to be presented using alternate-eye shutterglass technology, a development required because the dome screen precluded the use of polarized technology.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] From 1990 onward, numerous films were produced by all three parties to satisfy the demands of their various high-profile special attractions and IMAX's expanding 3D network.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Films of special note during this period include the extremely successful *Into the Deep* (Graeme Ferguson, 1995) and the first IMAX 3D fiction film *Wings of Courage* (1996), by director Jean-Jacques Annaud, about the pilot Henri Guillaumet.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] By 2004, 54% of IMAX theaters (133 of 248) were capable of showing 3D films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Shortly thereafter, higher quality computer animation, competition from DVDs and other media, digital projection, digital video capture, and the use of sophisticated IMAX 70mm film projectors, created an opportunity for another wave of 3D films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 2003, *Ghosts of the Abyss* by James Cameron was released as the first full-length 3D IMAX feature filmed with the Reality Camera System.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This camera system used the latest HD video cameras, not film, and was built for Cameron by Vince Pace, to his specifications.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The same camera system was used to film *Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over* (2003), *Aliens of the Deep* IMAX (2005), and *The Adventures of Sharkboy and Lavagirl in 3-D* (2005).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 2004, Las Vegas Hilton released Star Trek: The Experience which included two films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] One of the films, *Borg Invasion 4-D* (Ty Granoroli), was in 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In August of the same year, rap group Insane Clown Posse released their ninth studio album *Hell's Pit*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] One of two versions of the album contained a DVD featuring a 3D short film for the track "Bowling Balls", shot in high-definition video.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In November 2004, *The Polar Express* was released as IMAX's first full-length, animated 3D feature.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It was released in 3,584 theaters in 2D, and only 66 IMAX locations.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The return from those few 3D theaters was about 25% of the total.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The 3D version earned about 14 times as much per screen as the 2D version.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This pattern continued and prompted a greatly intensified interest in 3D and 3D presentation of animated films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In June 2005, the Mann's Chinese 6 theatre in Hollywood became the first commercial film theatre to be equipped with the Digital 3D format.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Both *Singin' in the Rain* and *The Polar Express* were tested in the Digital 3D format over the course of several months.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In November 2005, Walt Disney Pictures released *Chicken Little* in Digital 3D format.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Ben Walters suggested in 2009 that both filmmakers and film exhibitors regain interest in 3D film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] There was more 3D exhibition equipment, and more dramatic films being shot in 3D format.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] One incentive is that the technology is more mature.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Shooting in 3D format is less limited, and the result is more stable.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Another incentive was the fact that while 2D ticket sales were in an overall state of decline, revenues from 3D tickets continued to grow at the time.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Through the entire history of 3D presentations, techniques to convert existing 2D images for 3D presentation have existed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The combination of digital and digitized source material with relatively cost-effective digital post-processing has spawned a new wave of conversion products.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In June 2006, IMAX and Warner Bros. released *Superman Returns* including 20 minutes of 3D images converted from the 2D original digital footage.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] George Lucas announced that he would re-release his *Star Wars* films in 3D based on a conversion process from the company In-Three.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Later on in 2011, it was announced that Lucas was working with the company Prime Focus on this conversion.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In late 2005, Steven Spielberg told the press he was involved in patenting a 3D cinema system that did not need glasses, based on plasma screens.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] A computer splits each film-frame, and then projects the two split images onto the screen at differing angles, to be picked up by tiny angled ridges on the screen.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Animated films *Open Season*, and *The Ant Bully*, were released in analog 3D in 2006.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Monster House* and *The Nightmare Before Christmas* were released on XpanD 3D, RealD 3D and Dolby 3D systems in 2006.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] On May 19, 2007 *Scar3D* opened at the Cannes Film Market.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It was the first US-produced 3D full-length feature film to be completed in RealD 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It has been the #1 film at the box office in several countries around the world, including Russia where it opened in 3D on 295 screens.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] On January 19, 2008, U2 3D was released; it was the first live-action digital 3D film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the same year others 3D films included *Hannah Montana & Miley Cyrus: Best of Both Worlds Concert*, *Journey to the Center of the Earth*, and *Bolt*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] On January 16, 2009, Lionsgate released *My Bloody Valentine 3D*, the first horror film and first R-rated film to be projected in RealD 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It was released to 1,033 3D screens, the most ever for this format, and 1,501 regular screens.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Another R-rated film, *The Final Destination*, was released later that year in August on even more screens.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It was the first of its series to be released in HD 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Major 3D films in 2009 included *Coraline*, *Monsters vs.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Aliens*, *Up*, *X Games 3D: The Movie*, *The Final Destination*, *Disney's A Christmas Carol*, and *Avatar*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Avatar* has gone on to be one of the most expensive films of all time, with a budget at $237 million; it is also the highest-grossing film of all time.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The main technologies used to exhibit these films, and many others released around the time and up to the present, are RealD 3D, Dolby 3D, XpanD 3D, MasterImage 3D, and IMAX 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The success of the film also led to electronics manufacturers releasing 3D televisions and caused 3D films to increase in popularity.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] March and April 2010 saw three major 3D releases clustered together, with *Alice in Wonderland* hitting US theaters on March 5, 2010, *How to Train Your Dragon* on March 26, 2010, and *Clash of the Titans* on April 2, 2010.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] On May 13 of the same year, China's first IMAX 3D film started shooting.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The pre-production of the first 3D film shot in France, *Derrière les murs*, began in May 2010 and was released in mid-2011.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] On October 1, 2010 *Scar3D* was the first-ever stereoscopic 3D Video-on-demand film released through major cable broadcasters for 3D televisions in the United States.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Released in the United States on May 21, 2010, *Shrek Forever After* by DreamWorks Animation (Paramount Pictures) used the RealD 3D system, also released in IMAX 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In September 2003, Sabucat Productions organized the first World 3-D Exposition, celebrating the 50th anniversary of the original craze.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The Expo was held at Grauman's Egyptian Theatre.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In attendance were many stars from each film, respectively, and some were moved to tears by the sold-out seating with audiences of film buffs from all over the world who came to remember their previous glories.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In May 2006, the second World 3-D Exposition was announced for September of that year, presented by the 3-D Film Preservation Fund.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Along with the favorites of the previous exposition were newly discovered features and shorts, and like the previous Expo, guests from each film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Expo II was announced as being the locale for the world premiere of several films never before seen in 3D, including *The Diamond Wizard* and the Universal short, *Hawaiian Nights* with Mamie Van Doren and Pinky Lee.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Other "re-premieres" of films not seen since their original release in stereoscopic form included *Cease Fire!*, *Taza, Son of Cochise*, *Wings of the Hawk*, and *Those Redheads From Seattle*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Also shown were the long-lost shorts *Carmenesque* and *A Day in the Country* (both 1953) and William Van Doren Kelley's two *Plasticon* shorts (1922 and 1923).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the wake of its initial popularity and corresponding increase in the number of screens, more films were being released in the 3D format, yet fewer people were choosing to see them in such a way.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] For instance, only 45% of the premiere weekend box office earnings of *Kung Fu Panda 2* in 2011 came from 3D screenings as opposed to 60% for *Shrek Forever After* in 2010.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In addition, the premiere of *Cars 2* opening weekend gross consisted of only 37% from 3D theatres.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 2* and *Captain America: The First Avenger* were major releases that achieved similar percentages: 43% and 40% respectively.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In view of this trend, there has been box office analysis concluding the implementation of 3D presentation is apparently backfiring by discouraging people from going to film theatres at all.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] As Brandon Gray of Box Office Mojo notes, "In each case, 3D's more-money-from-fewer-people approach has simply led to less money from even fewer people." Parallel, the number of televisions sold with support for 3D television has dropped, let alone those sold with actual 3D goggles.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] According to the Motion Picture Association of America, despite a record total of 47 3D films being released in 2011, the overall domestic box office receipts were down 18% to $1.8 billion from $2.2 billion in 2010.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Although revenues as a whole increased during 2012, the bulk has so far come from 2D presentations as exemplified by little over 50% of filmgoers opting to see the likes of *The Avengers* and 32% choosing *Brave* in their 3D versions.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Conflicting reasons are respectively offered by studios and exhibitors: whereas the former blame more expensive 3D ticket prices, the latter argue that the quality of films in general is at fault.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] However, despite the perceived decline of 3D in the U.S. market, studio chiefs in 2012 were optimistic of better receipts internationally, where there still appeared to be a strong appetite for the format.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Studios are also using 3D to generate additional income from films that are already commercially successful.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Such re-releases usually involve a conversion from 2D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] For example, Disney has reissued both *The Lion King* and *Beauty and the Beast*, with plans to add some of its other well-known titles.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Titanic* has also been modified for 3D, and there are also plans to similarly present all six *Star Wars* films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Jeffrey Katzenberg, a producer of 3D films and one of the leading proponents of the format, blames oversaturation of the market with inferior films, especially ones photographed conventionally and then digitally processed in post-production.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] He claims that such films have led audiences to conclude that the format is not worth the often much higher ticket price.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Daniel Engber, a columnist for *Slate*, comes to a similar conclusion: "What happened to 3-D?
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Film critic Mark Kermode, a noted detractor of 3D, has surmised that there is an emerging policy of distributors to limit the availability of 2D versions, thus "railroading" the 3D format into cinemas whether the paying filmgoer likes it or not.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This was especially prevalent during the release of *Prometheus* in 2012, where only 30% of prints for theatrical exhibition (at least in the UK) were in 2D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] His suspicions were later reinforced by a substantial number of complaints about *Dredd* from those who wished to see it in 2D but were denied the opportunity.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In July 2017, IMAX announced that they would begin to focus on screening more Hollywood tentpole movies in 2D (even if there's a 3D version) and have fewer 3D screenings of movies in North America, citing that moviegoers in North America prefer 2D films over 3D films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 2024, 3D films in 4K HDR became available to home media for the first time, with the launch of the visionOS operating system offering two services to access movies in such formats: Apple TV and Disney+.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Some films were also offered in high frame rate (48fps), such as *Avatar: The Way of Water*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 2025, 3D films became available to Android XR devices via the Google TV service, starting with the Samsung Galaxy XR.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Stereoscopic motion pictures can be produced through a variety of different methods.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Over the years the popularity of systems being widely employed in film theaters has waxed and waned.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Though anaglyph was sometimes used prior to 1948, during the early "Golden Era" of 3D cinematography of the 1950s the polarization system was used for every single feature-length film in the United States, and all but one short film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the 21st century, polarization 3D systems have continued to dominate the scene, though during the 1960s and 1970s some classic films which were converted to anaglyph for theaters not equipped for polarization, and were even shown in 3D on television.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the years following the mid-1980s, some films were made with short segments in anaglyph 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The following are some of the technical details and methodologies employed in some of the more notable 3D film systems that have been developed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The standard for shooting live-action films in 3D involves using two cameras mounted so that their lenses are about as far apart from each other as the average pair of human eyes, recording two separate images for both the left eye and the right eye.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In principle, two normal 2D cameras could be put side-to-side but this is problematic in many ways.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The only real option is to invest in new stereoscopic cameras.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Moreover, some cinematographic tricks that are simple with a 2D camera become impossible when filming in 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This means those otherwise cheap tricks need to be replaced by expensive CGI.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 2008, *Journey to the Center of the Earth* became the first live-action feature film to be shot with the earliest Fusion Camera System released in Digital 3D and was later followed by several others.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Avatar* (2009) was shot in a 3D process that is based on how the human eye looks at an image.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It was an improvement to the existing 3D camera system.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Many 3D camera rigs still in use simply pair two cameras side by side, while newer rigs are paired with a beam splitter or both camera lenses built into one unit.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] While Digital Cinema cameras are not a requirement for 3D they are the predominant medium for most of what is photographed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Film options include IMAX 3D and Cine 160.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the 1930s and 1940s, the Fleischer Studios made several cartoons with extensive stereoscopic 3D backgrounds, including several *Popeye the Sailor*, *Betty Boop*, and *Superman* cartoons.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the early to mid-1950s, only half of the major Animation film studios operation experimented with creating traditional 3D animated short subjects.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The Walt Disney Studio produced two traditionally animated shorts in stereoscopic 3D, for cinemas.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] *Adventures in Music: Melody* (1953), and the Donald Duck cartoon *Working for Peanuts* (1953).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Cartoons only produced a single cartoon in 3D: *Lumber Jack-Rabbit* (1953) starring Bugs Bunny.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Famous Studios produced two cartoons in 3D, the Popeye cartoon *Popeye, the Ace of Space* (1953), and the Casper the Friendly Ghost cartoon *Boo Moon* (1954).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Walter Lantz Productions produced the Woody Woodpecker cartoon *Hypnotic Hick* (1953), which was distributed by Universal.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] From the late 1950s until the mid-2000s almost no animation was produced for 3D display in theaters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Although several films used 3D backgrounds.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] One exception is *Starchaser: The Legend of Orin*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] CGI animated films can be rendered as stereoscopic 3D version by using two virtual cameras.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Stop-motion animated 3D films are photographed with two cameras similar to live action 3D films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In 2004 *The Polar Express* was the first stereoscopic 3D CGI-animated feature film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The 3D version was solely released in IMAX theaters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In November 2005, Walt Disney Pictures released *Chicken Little* in Digital 3D format, being Disney's first CGI-animated film in 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The film was converted from 2D into 3D in post-production. nWave Pictures' *Fly Me to the Moon* (2008) was actually the first animated film created for 3D and released exclusively in 3D in digital theaters around the world.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] No other animation films have released solely in 3D since.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The first 3D feature by DreamWorks Animation, *Monsters vs.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Aliens*, followed in 2009 and used a new digital rendering process called InTru3D, which was developed by Intel to create more realistic animated 3D images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] InTru3D is not used to exhibit 3D films in theaters; they are shown in either RealD 3D or IMAX 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the case of 2D CGI animated films that were generated from 3D models, it is possible to return to the models to generate a 3D version.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] For all other 2D films, different techniques must be employed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] For example, for the 3D re-release of the 1993 film *The Nightmare Before Christmas*, Walt Disney Pictures scanned each original frame and manipulated them to produce left-eye and right-eye versions.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Dozens of films have now been converted from 2D to 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] There are several approaches used for 2D to 3D conversion, most notably depth-based methods.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Information is unavailable as 2D does not have information for a perspective view.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Some TVs have a 3D engine to convert 2D content to 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Usually, on high frame rate content (and on some slower processors even normal frame rate) the processor is not fast enough and lag is possible.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This can lead to strange visual effects.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Anaglyph images were the earliest method of presenting theatrical 3D, and the one most commonly associated with stereoscopy by the public at large, mostly because of non-theatrical 3D media such as comic books and 3D television broadcasts, where polarization is not practical.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] They were made popular because of the ease of their production and exhibition.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The first anaglyph film was invented in 1915 by Edwin S Porter.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Though the earliest theatrical presentations were done with this system, most 3D films from the 1950s and 1980s were originally shown polarized.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In an anaglyph, the two images are superimposed in an additive light setting through two filters, one red and one cyan.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In a subtractive light setting, the two images are printed in the same complementary colors on white paper.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Glasses with colored filters in each eye separate the appropriate images by canceling the filter color out and rendering the complementary color black.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Anaglyph images are much easier to view than either parallel sighting or crossed eye stereograms, although the latter types offer bright and accurate color rendering, particularly in the red component, which is muted, or desaturated with even the best color anaglyphs.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] A compensating technique, commonly known as Anachrome, uses a slightly more transparent cyan filter in the patented glasses associated with the technique.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Process reconfigures the typical anaglyph image to have less parallax.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] An alternative to the usual red and cyan filter system of anaglyph is ColorCode 3-D, a patented anaglyph system which was invented in order to present an anaglyph image in conjunction with the NTSC television standard, in which the red channel is often compromised.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] ColorCode uses the complementary colors of yellow and dark blue on-screen, and the colors of the glasses' lenses are amber and dark blue.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The polarization 3D system has been the standard for theatrical presentations since it was used for *Bwana Devil* in 1952, though early IMAX presentations were done using the eclipse system and in the 1960s and 1970s classic 3D films were sometimes converted to anaglyph for special presentations.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The polarization system has better color fidelity and less ghosting than the anaglyph system.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the post-'50s era, anaglyph has been used instead of polarization in feature presentations where only part of the film is in 3D such as in the 3D segment of *Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare* and the 3D segments of *Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over*.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Anaglyph is also used in printed materials and in 3D television broadcasts where polarization is not practical.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] 3D polarized televisions and other displays only became available from several manufacturers in 2008; these generate polarization on the receiving end.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] To present a stereoscopic motion pictures, two images are projected superimposed onto the same screen through different polarizing filters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The viewer wears low-cost glasses which also contain a pair of polarizing filters oriented differently (clockwise/counterclockwise with circular polarization or at 90 degree angles, usually 45 and 135 degrees, with linear polarization).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] As each filter passes only that light which is similarly polarized and blocks the light polarized differently, each eye sees a different image.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This is used to produce a three-dimensional effect by projecting the same scene into both eyes, but depicted from slightly different perspectives.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Since no head tracking is involved, the entire audience can view the stereoscopic images at the same time.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Circular polarization has an advantage over linear polarization, in that the viewer does not need to have their head upright and aligned with the screen for the polarization to work properly.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] With linear polarization, turning the glasses sideways causes the filters to go out of alignment with the screen filters causing the image to fade and for each eye to see the opposite frame more easily.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] For circular polarization, the polarizing effect works regardless of how the viewer's head is aligned with the screen such as tilted sideways, or even upside down.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The left eye will still only see the image intended for it, and vice versa, without fading or crosstalk.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Nonetheless, 3D cinema films are made to be viewed without head tilt, and any significant head tilt will result in incorrect parallax and prevent binocular fusion.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the case of RealD a circularly polarizing liquid crystal filter which can switch polarity 144 times per second is placed in front of the projector lens.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Only one projector is needed, as the left and right eye images are displayed alternately.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Sony features a new system called RealD XLS, which shows both circular polarized images simultaneously: A single 4K projector (4096×2160 resolution) displays both 2K images (2048×1080 resolution) on top of each other at the same time, a special lens attachment polarizes and projects the images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Optical attachments can be added to traditional 35 mm projectors to adapt them for projecting film in the "over-and-under" format, in which each pair of images is stacked within one frame of film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The two images are projected through different polarizers and superimposed on the screen.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This is a very cost-effective way to convert a theater for 3D as all that is needed are the attachments and a non-depolarizing screen surface, rather than a conversion to digital 3D projection.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Thomson Technicolor currently produces an adapter of this type.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] A metallic screen is necessary for these systems as reflection from non-metallic surfaces destroys the polarization of the light.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Polarized stereoscopic pictures have been around since 1936, when Edwin H.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Land first applied it to motion pictures.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The so-called "3-D movie craze" in the years 1952 through 1955 was almost entirely offered in theaters using linear polarizing projection and glasses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Only a minute amount of the total 3D films shown in the period used the anaglyph color filter method.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Linear polarization was likewise used with consumer level stereo projectors.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Polarization was also used during the 3D revival of the 1980s.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In the 2000s, computer animation, competition from DVDs and other media, digital projection, and the use of sophisticated IMAX 70 mm film projectors, have created an opportunity for a new wave of polarized 3D films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] All types of polarization will result in a darkening of the displayed image and poorer contrast compared to non-3D images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Light from lamps is normally emitted as a random collection of polarizations, while a polarization filter only passes a fraction of the light.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] As a result, the screen image is darker.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This darkening can be compensated by increasing the brightness of the projector light source.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] If the initial polarization filter is inserted between the lamp and the image generation element, the light intensity striking the image element is not any higher than normal without the polarizing filter, and overall image contrast transmitted to the screen is not affected.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In this technology, a mechanism is used to block light from each appropriate eye when the converse eye's image is projected on the screen.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The technology originated with the Eclipse Method, in which the projector alternates between left and right images, and opens and closes the shutters in the glasses or viewer in synchronization with the images on the screen.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This was the basis of the Teleview system which was used briefly in 1922.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] A newer implementation of the Eclipse Method came with liquid-crystal shutter glasses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Glasses containing liquid crystal that will let light through in synchronization with the images on the cinema, television or computer screen, using the concept of alternate-frame sequencing.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This is the method used by nVidia, XpanD 3D, and earlier IMAX systems.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] A drawback of this method is the need for each person viewing to wear expensive, electronic glasses that must be synchronized with the display system using a wireless signal or attached wire.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The shutter-glasses are heavier than most polarized glasses, though lighter models are no heavier than some sunglasses or deluxe polarized glasses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] However these systems do not require a silver screen for projected images.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Liquid crystal light valves work by rotating light between two polarizing filters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Due to these internal polarizers, LCD shutter-glasses darken the display image of any LCD, plasma, or projector image source, which has the result that images appear dimmer and contrast is lower than for normal non-3D viewing.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This is not necessarily a usage problem; for some types of displays which are already very bright with poor grayish black levels, LCD shutter glasses may actually improve the image quality.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Dolby 3D uses specific wavelengths of red, green, and blue for the right eye, and different wavelengths of red, green, and blue for the left eye.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Glasses which filter out the very specific wavelengths allow the wearer to see a 3D image.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This technology eliminates the expensive silver screens required for polarized systems such as RealD, which is the most common 3D display system in theaters.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It does, however, require much more expensive glasses than the polarized systems.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The recently introduced Omega 3D/Panavision 3D system also uses this technology, though with a wider spectrum and more "teeth" to the "comb" (5 for each eye in the Omega/Panavision system).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The use of more spectral bands per eye eliminates the need to color process the image, required by the Dolby system.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Evenly dividing the visible spectrum between the eyes gives the viewer a more relaxed "feel" as the light energy and color balance is nearly 50-50.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Like the Dolby system, the Omega system can be used with white or silver screens.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] But it can be used with either film or digital projectors, unlike the Dolby filters that are only used on a digital system with a color correcting processor provided by Dolby.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The Omega/Panavision system also claims that their glasses are cheaper to manufacture than those used by Dolby.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In June 2012 the Omega 3D/Panavision 3D system was discontinued by DPVO Theatrical, who marketed it on behalf of Panavision, citing "challenging global economic and 3D market conditions".
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Although DPVO dissolved its business operations, Omega Optical continues promoting and selling 3D systems to non-theatrical markets.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Omega Optical's 3D system contains projection filters and 3D glasses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In addition to the passive stereoscopic 3D system, Omega Optical has produced enhanced anaglyph 3D glasses.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The Omega's red/cyan anaglyph glasses use complex metal oxide thin film coatings and high quality annealed glass optics.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In this method, glasses are not necessary to see a 3D image.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] To produce the 3D effect, the person must be positioned so that one eye sees one of the two images and the other sees the other.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Both images are projected onto a high-gain, corrugated screen that reflects light at acute angles.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] In order to see the stereoscopic image, the viewer must sit within a very narrow angle that is nearly perpendicular to the screen, limiting the size of the audience.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Lenticular was used for theatrical presentation of numerous shorts in Russia from 1940 to 1948 and in 1946 for the feature-length film Robinson Crusoe.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Though lenticular's use in theatrical presentations has been rather limited, it has been widely used for a variety of novelty items and has even been used in amateur 3D photography.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Recent use includes the Fujifilm FinePix Real 3D with an autostereoscopic display that was released in 2009.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Other examples for this technology include autostereoscopic liquid crystal displays on monitors, notebooks, TVs, mobile phones and gaming devices, such as the Nintendo 3DS.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Some viewers have complained of headaches and eyestrain after watching 3D films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Motion sickness, in addition to other health concerns, are more easily induced by 3D presentations.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] One published study shows that of those who watch 3D films, nearly 55% experience varying levels of headaches, nausea and disorientation.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] Glasses designed to eliminate eyestrain by converting 3D images back into 2D have been developed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] It is believed that approximately 12% of people are unable to properly see 3D images, due to a variety of medical conditions.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] According to another experiment up to 30% of people have very weak stereoscopic vision preventing them from depth perception based on stereo disparity.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] This nullifies or greatly decreases immersion effects of digital stereo to them.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p02] The French National Research Agency (ANR) has sponsored multidisciplinary research in order to understand the effects of 3D film viewing, its grammar, and its acceptance.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Most of the cues required to provide humans with relative depth information are already present in traditional 2D films.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] In fact, only two of these depth cues are not already present in 2D films: stereopsis (or parallax) and the focus of the eyeball (accommodation).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] 3D film-making addresses accurate presentation of stereopsis but not of accommodation, and therefore is insufficient in providing a complete 3D illusion.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] However, promising results from research aimed at overcoming this shortcoming were presented at the 2010 Stereoscopic Displays and Applications conference in San Jose, U.S.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Film critic Mark Kermode argued that 3D adds "not that much" value to a film, and said that, while he liked *Avatar*, the many impressive things he saw in the film had nothing to do with 3D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Kermode has been an outspoken critic of 3D film describing the effect as a "nonsense" and recommends using two right or left lenses from the 3D glasses to cut out the "pointy, pointy 3D stereoscopic vision", although this technique still does not improve the huge brightness loss from a 3D film.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Versions of these "2-D glasses" are being marketed.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Director Christopher Nolan has criticised the notion that traditional film does not allow depth perception, saying "I think it's a misnomer to call it 3D versus 2D.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] The whole point of cinematic imagery is it's three dimensional...
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Late film critic Roger Ebert repeatedly criticized 3D film as being "too dim", sometimes distracting or even nausea-inducing, and argued that it is an expensive technology that adds nothing of value to the film-going experience (since 2-D films already provide a sufficient illusion of 3D).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] While Ebert was "not opposed to 3-D as an option", he opposed it as a replacement for traditional film, and preferred 2-D technologies such as MaxiVision48 that improve image area/resolution and frames per second.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Most 3D systems will cut down the brightness of the picture considerably – the light loss can be as high as 88%.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Some of this loss may be compensated by running the projector's bulb at higher power or using more powerful bulbs.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] The 2D brightness cinema standard is 14 foot-lamberts (48 candela per square metre), as set by the SMPTE standard 196M.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] As of 2012, there is no official standard for 3D brightness.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] According to the industry de facto standard, however, the "acceptable brightness range" goes as low as 3.5 fL (12 cd/m2) – just 25% of the standard 2D brightness.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] In September 2012, the DCI standards body issued a "recommended practice" calling for a 3D projection brightness of 7 fL (24 cd/m2), with an acceptable range of 5–9 fL (17–31 cd/m2).
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] It is not known how many theaters actually achieve such light levels with current technology.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Prototype laser projection systems have reached 14 fL (48 cd/m2) for 3D on a cinema screen.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Another major criticism is that many of the films in the 21st century to date were not filmed in 3D, but converted to 3D after filming.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Filmmakers who have criticized the quality of this process include James Cameron (whose film *Avatar* was created mostly in 3D from the ground up, with some portions of the film created in 2D, and is largely credited with the revival of 3D) and Michael Bay.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] However, Cameron has said that quality 2D to 3D conversions can be done if they take the time they need and the director is involved.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] Cameron's *Titanic* was converted into 3D in 2012, taking 60 weeks and costing $18 million.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] In contrast, computer-animated films for which the original computer models are still available can be rendered in 3D easily, as the depth information is still available and does not need to be inferred or approximated.
[src:documentary-film/3d-film-p03] This has been done with *Toy Story*, among others.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The events inspired the 1964 song "Birmingham Sunday" by Richard and Mimi Fariña, which was used in the opening sequence of the film, as sung by Joan Baez, Mimi's sister.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] They also inspired the 1963 tune "Alabama" by John Coltrane, which is also included in the soundtrack.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] In 2017, the film was selected for preservation in the United States National Film Registry by the Library of Congress as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant".
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] A local chapter of the Ku Klux Klan placed bombs at the 16th Street Baptist Church and set them off as Sunday services prepared to commence on the morning of September 15, 1963.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Four young girls, ranging in age from 11 to 14, were killed in the explosion, which also caused anywhere between 14 and 22 additional injuries.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The deaths provoked national outrage, and, the following summer, the United States Congress passed the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which was signed by President Lyndon B.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The bombing is marked in history as a critical and pivotal moment in the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The film covered the events in Birmingham, Alabama, in 1963 related to civil rights demonstrations and the movement to end racial discrimination in local stores and facilities.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Martin Luther King Jr. arrived in the town to help with their strategy and to speak at the funeral of the four young girls.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] People of the community met at the 16th Street Baptist Church while organizing their events.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The demonstrations were covered by national media, and the use by police of police dogs and pressured water from hoses on young people shocked the nation.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The large number of demonstrators who were arrested resulted in local jails filling capacity.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The film ends with the trial and conviction in 1977 of Robert Edward Chambliss, also known as Dynamite Bob, as the main person responsible for the bombing, though he is said to have been only one of four Klan members involved.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The film also references black churches being set on fire in Birmingham in 1993, giving the impression that, while progress has been made, there are some things that still have not changed.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Lee uses interviews with family and friends of the girls, government officials, and civil rights activists, as well as home movies and archival footage, to not only tell the story of the four girls' lives but also to provide a greater historical and political context of the times.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Lee first became interested in making a film about the Birmingham bombing in 1983, when he was a student at New York University.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] After reading a *New York Times Magazine* article about the incident, he was moved to write to Chris McNair, the father of Denise, one of the victims, to ask for permission to tell her story on film.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] McNair turned down the young, aspiring filmmaker.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] "I was entering my first semester at N.Y.U.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] So my skills as a filmmaker were nonexistent, and at that time, Chris McNair was still hesitant to talk about it," Lee said in a 1997 interview with Industry Central's The Director's Chair.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] According to McNair, he changed his mind about supporting Lee's film idea due to learning about the depth and precision of Lee's research.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] McNair said, "[I]t's very important that this be done accurately and correctly.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] In all his research, he [Lee] showed that he was objective and seeking a broad section of opinion.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] At first, Lee had intended to create a dramatic reproduction of the incident, but eventually, he decided that would not be the best approach, and the project became a documentary.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Once he secured funding, he went to Birmingham with a small skeleton film crew, as he wanted the families to be as comfortable as possible during the interviews.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Sam Pollard served as a producer and the editor and Ellen Kuras was the director of photography of the film.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Lee had developed a relationship with Kuras while working on an HBO project called *Subway Stories*, which was an anthology of short films compiled by Jonathan Demme (though Lee's film did not make the final cut due, in part, to conflict between him and Demme).
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Kuras said of her desire to shoot *4 Little Girls*, "I was really interested because my background is in political documentaries ...
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] I always felt that one of the reasons that I had got into filmmaking was that I wanted to use my craft to be able to say something about the human condition, however I could, in my own humble way.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Lee's partnership with Sam Pollard had begun on *Mo' Better Blues* when Pollard was recommended to replace Barry Alexander Brown, who was unavailable because he was directing his own film, as editor.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Pollard originally refused the overture because he was busy working on his segments of *Eyes on the Prize*, but ultimately, he accepted, and he has since become one of Lee's most frequent collaborators.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Their first few films together were fiction, but Pollard's background was in documentary, and he was key to guiding the structure of *4 Little Girls*.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] The film was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] On Rotten Tomatoes, it holds an approval rating of 100% based on 25 reviews, with an average rating of 8.42/10.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Metacritic, which uses a weighted average, assigned the film a score of 88 out of 100, based on 16 critics, indicating "universal acclaim".
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] It was initially planned for the film to first be seen by the public when it was aired on HBO, but, after seeing the final product, the production team decided it was important to release the film in theaters before running it on television.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] Accordingly, *4 Little Girls* opened in American theaters on July 9, 1997, and closed on October 2, 1997.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] It grossed $130,146 from a total of four theaters.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] In its opening weekend, it earned $13,528 from a single theater, which was 10.4% of its total gross.
[src:documentary-film/4-little-girls] It cost approximately $1 million to make, funded by HBO.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The film states that the lasting effects of slavery are still felt 500 years later, hence the title.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] This is justified and explained through a series of scholarly interviews throughout the film.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The film includes testimonies, voices, and opinions gathered around five continents.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Many of the people who voice their opinion are scholars or experts on the African diaspora.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Those interviewed in the film criticize contemporary rap music as being particularly negative for Africans and their descendants, as they believe it reinforced racist stereotypes that were established in part because of the slave trade.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] A lasting example of the stereotypes referenced in the film is a study performed by Kenneth and Mamie Clark in which black children were given a variety of dolls, including black and white ones, and were told to pick the "smarter" or "better" one.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] A majority of the black children chose the white dolls.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Many of those interviewed believe that a distinct change to the educational system is necessary to change the mindset of people of African descent.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The film affirms that "the kind of education that we have is to still enslave our minds, to make us believe we are inferior." Education should be the main weapon for the new generations of Africans and African descendants, to remind the world of the richness and struggle of African history.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] At the end of the film, Africans are encouraged to remember their past, in order to move forward.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The film promotes the idea that making it through enslavement should be a strength, not a weakness or something to be ashamed about; that the people who enslaved the Africans should be the ones that are ashamed.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Essentially, the goal proposed is to teach African children a more Afrocentric history, instead of a Eurocentric one.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] It further argues that teaching African-descent people about a history that is not their own will not help because they cannot relate to it.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] It also indicates that society must establish and promote African ideas and history in order to preserve what they want for future generations.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The film calls for the ideas promoted within it to become mainstream so that there can be a better Africa and a better history associated with the continent.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The cast features key figures from the African-American academic world.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Kingsley Sheteh, from *A Neo-Copernican Review*, asserts that *500 Years Later* is a step in the right direction in depicting the relationship between the Western world and Africa, showcasing the historically dependent and underdeveloped status of African countries.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Shetah also pointed out that, although the movie does well with sensitive issues that are causes for Africa's problems, it fails to treat the issue of conflict.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Shetah cites reasons that independent African state governments are heavily corrupted due to problems that can't simply be tied down to ideology, slavery, and colonialism.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] While not exactly presenting new information, the documentary's delivery of the material and evidence is refreshing, meant to promote discussion among groups of people.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Many critics received the film as a way to explore African history like never before.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The film is a compilation of interviews that offer history from the perspective of people whose knowledge has been suppressed for years.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] *500 Years Later* is applauded for its vast focus on African history, both the good and the bad.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Though successful, *500 Years Later* received mixed reviews from critics regarding content and presentation.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Dan Schindel, a documentary reviewer, calls the film "The Malcolm X to the MLK of the average doc that covers African-related material" and offers many examples of the extremity of the film.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] The article "Destroying the Horrors of 500 Years" by Attahiru Kawu-Bala praised the film as an "articulate multi-dimensional African world perspective" with regard to the effects of African Diaspora.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] Kawu-Bala argued that the techniques used in the documentary did not rely on emotion and instead used facts and truth to build a case from an African standpoint.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] By contrast, Curt Holman recognized the film's righteousness, but believed "a more informative film would have been more effective." He found the video to be emotionally charged and, at times, overly obvious.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] According to Holman, the emotional biases sometimes overshadowed the factual content.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] According to Kahiu, *500 Years Later* is a good resource to show the challenges people of African descent faced during the Diaspora and slavery and the challenges they still face today.
[src:documentary-film/500-years-later] She further states that the film is a great representation of the strength of African-American culture and citizenry, and claims that the movie is a call for African people to patiently work to rid the African world of the "defeatist nature" still subconsciously ingrained in them today.
[src:documentary-film/a-diary-for-timothy] These include the recovery of an English fighter pilot Dr.
[src:documentary-film/a-diary-for-timothy] He received AAA fire while attacking a German 5th Army Group panzer column that was blocking the advance to Caen.
[src:documentary-film/a-diary-for-timothy] He was wounded through the right lower leg and yet was able to parachute from his disabled fighter.
[src:documentary-film/a-diary-for-timothy] Also featured are a coal miner, Goronwy, with a broken arm; Allan, a farmer; and Bill, a locomotive engine driver.
[src:documentary-film/a-diary-for-timothy] Dame Myra Hess is featured giving a concert at the National Gallery in London, several years after her appearance in *Listen to Britain* (1942), and John Gielgud performs as the Prince in the gravediggers scene from *Hamlet*.
[src:documentary-film/a-diary-for-timothy] In a 2000 documentary about Jennings made for Channel 4 television by Kevin MacDonald, it was revealed that the baby who was the subject of the film (Timothy James Jenkins) later moved to Brighton in the 1960s and became a mod before settling down to become a teacher; he died in November 2000.
[src:documentary-film/ab-ovo] This advice is famously rejected in Laurence Sterne's novel *The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman*.
[src:documentary-film/ab-ovo] This use is distinct from the longer phrase *ab ovo usque ad mala* (lit.
[src:documentary-film/ab-ovo] "from the egg to the apples") which appears in Horace's *Satire* 1.3.
[src:documentary-film/ab-ovo] It refers to the course of a Roman meal, which often began with eggs and ended with fruit, and is similar to the American English phrase "soup to nuts".
[src:documentary-film/ab-ovo] Thus *ab ovo* can also be used to mean a complete or entire thing.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] The term can be used more generally to refer to anything that is prominently displayed or of highest priority.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Above the fold is sometimes used in web development to refer the portions of a webpage that are visible without further scrolling or clicking.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] In contrast, portions available via clickthrough are sometimes described as "after the jump".
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Above the fold is also used in website design (along with "above the scroll") to refer to the portion of the webpage that is visible without scrolling.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] As screen sizes vary drastically there is no set definition for the number of pixels that define the fold.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] This is because different screen resolutions will show different portions of the website without scrolling.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Further complicating matters, many websites adjust their layout based on the size of the browser window, such that the fold is not a static feature of the page.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] A 2006 study by Jakob Nielsen found that 77% of visitors to a website do not scroll, and therefore only see the portion of the website that is above the fold.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] In a more recent article by Amy Schade and NNgroup it is stated that there is an 84% average difference in how users treat the content above and below the fold, there is a big dropoff in attention below the fold.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Most web design advice available today encourages designers to place important information at the top of the website, but also to prioritize usability and design.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Nevertheless, many web advertising companies require ads be placed above the fold.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Marketing research done by Google shows that the viewability of adverts is affected by its position in relation to the fold as there is a significant drop-off below the fold.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Each company tends to use their own definition of the fold.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] The BlogHer advertising network, for example, defines the fold as the top 768 pixels of the page.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] The FoodieBlogRoll advertising network defines the fold as the top 1000 pixels.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Internet search query results appear much in the same way.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Many web site optimization efforts may be exerted in an attempt to gain the highest "search indexing" or "ranking" placement (as close to first place as possible) for directed term(s) or phrase(s).
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Using natural or "organic" web site optimization practices has been the standard operating procedure for attaining higher indexing with the result being the web site appearing in the view area or "above the fold" of the search results pages and especially the first page.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] The term is infrequently used in reference to resume and CV (curriculum vitae) layout, where the most crucial and relevant (to the job sought) information must be in the top third, alternately called the "hot zone", to catch the attention of the reader.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] Since most applicants file credentials electronically, and applications are no longer folded in thirds to fit in an envelope, the advice remains, even though the means of distribution has changed.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] "Below the fold" refers to the parts of a newspaper or tabloid that are not on the first half of the first page, and are therefore less prominent.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] It can also refer to the portion of a webpage that does not show until one scrolls down.
[src:documentary-film/above-the-fold] When Apple was ordered to display acknowledgements that Samsung did *not* infringe their designs, complaints surfaced because JavaScript code on its UK webpage kept the acknowledgement hidden "below the fold".
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] A **documentary film** (often called simply a **documentary**) is a nonfiction motion picture intended to "document reality, primarily for instruction, education or maintaining a historical record".
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The American author and media analyst Bill Nichols has characterized the documentary in terms of "a filmmaking practice, a cinematic tradition, and mode of audience reception [that remains] a practice without clear boundaries".
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Research into information gathering, as a behavior, and the sharing of knowledge, as a concept, has noted how documentary movies were preceded by the notable practice of documentary photography.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] This has involved the use of singular photographs to detail the complex attributes of historical events and continues to a certain degree to this day, with an example being the conflict-related photography achieved by popular figures such as Mathew Brady during the American Civil War.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentary movies evolved from the creation of singular images in order to convey particular types of information in depth, using film as a medium.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Early documentary films, originally called "actuality films", briefly lasted for one minute or less in most cases.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] While faithfully depicting true events, these releases possessed no narrative structure per se and were of limited interest.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Over time, documentaries have evolved to become longer in length and to include more categories of information.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Some examples are explicitly educational, while others serve as observational works; docufiction movies notably include aspects of dramatic storytelling that are clearly fictional.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentaries are informative at times, and certain types are often used within schools as a resource to teach various principles.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentary filmmakers have a responsibility to be truthful to their vision of the world without intentionally misrepresenting a topic.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Social media organizations, such as Dailymotion and YouTube, with many of these platforms receiving popular interest, have provided an avenue for the growth of documentaries as a particular film genre.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Such platforms have increased the distribution area and ease-of-accessibility given the ability of online video sharing to spread to multiple audiences at once as well as to work past certain socio-political hurdles such as censorship.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Polish writer and filmmaker Bolesław Matuszewski was among those who identified the mode of documentary film.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] He wrote two of the earliest texts on cinema, *Une nouvelle source de l'histoire* ("A New Source of History") and *La photographie animée* ("Animated photography").
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Both were published in 1898 in French and were among the earliest written works to consider the historical and documentary value of the film.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Matuszewski is also among the first filmmakers to propose the creation of a Film Archive to collect and keep safe visual materials.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The word "documentary" was coined by Scottish documentary filmmaker John Grierson in his review of Robert Flaherty's film *Moana* (1926), published in the *New York Sun* on 8 February 1926, written by "The Moviegoer" (a pen name for Grierson).
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The American film critic Pare Lorentz defines a documentary film as "a factual film which is dramatic." Others further state that a documentary stands out from the other types of non-fiction films for providing an opinion, and a specific message, along with the facts it presents.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Scholar Betsy McLane asserted that documentaries are for filmmakers to convey their views about historical events, people, and places which they find significant.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Therefore, the advantage of documentaries lies in introducing new perspectives which may not be prevalent in traditional media such as written publications and school curricula.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentary practice is the complex process of creating documentary projects.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] It refers to what people do with media devices, content, form, and production strategies to address the creative, ethical, and conceptual problems and choices that arise as they make documentaries.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentary filmmaking can be used as a form of journalism, advocacy, or personal expression.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Early film (pre-1900) was dominated by the novelty of showing an event.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Single-shot moments were captured on film, such as a train entering a station, a boat docking, or factory workers leaving work.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] These short films were called "actuality" films; the term "documentary" was not coined until 1926.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Many of the first films, such as those made by Auguste and Louis Lumière, were a minute or less in length, due to technological limitations.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Films showing many people (for example, leaving a factory) were often made for commercial reasons: the people being filmed were eager to see, for payment, the film showing them.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] One notable film clocked in at over an hour and a half, *The Corbett-Fitzsimmons Fight*.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Using pioneering film-looping technology, Enoch J.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Rector presented the entirety of a famous 1897 prize-fight on cinema screens across the United States.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In May 1896, Bolesław Matuszewski recorded on film a few surgical operations in Warsaw and Saint Petersburg hospitals.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In 1898, French surgeon Eugène-Louis Doyen invited Matuszewski and Clément Maurice to record his surgical operations.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] They started in Paris a series of surgical films sometime before July 1898.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Until 1906, the year of his last film, Doyen recorded more than 60 operations.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Doyen said that his first films taught him how to correct professional errors he had been unaware of.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] For scientific purposes, after 1906, Doyen combined 15 of his films into three compilations, two of which survive, the six-film series *Extirpation des tumeurs encapsulées* (1906), and the four-film *Les Opérations sur la cavité crânienne* (1911).
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] These and five other of Doyen's films survive.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] All these short films have been preserved.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The professor called his works "studies with the help of the cinematograph," and published the results, along with several consecutive frames, in issues of *La Semaine Médicale* magazine from Paris, between 1899 and 1902.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] I must say I forgot those works and I am thankful to you that you reminded them to me.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Travelogue films were very popular in the early part of the 20th century.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] They were often referred to by distributors as "scenics".
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Scenics were among the most popular sort of films at the time.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] An important early film which moved beyond the concept of the scenic was *In the Land of the Head Hunters* (1914), which embraced primitivism and exoticism in a staged story presented as truthful re-enactments of the life of Native Americans.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Pathé was the best-known global manufacturer of such films in the early 20th century.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] A vivid example is *Moscow Clad in Snow* (1909).
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Biographical documentaries appeared during this time, such as the feature *Eminescu-Veronica-Creangă* (1914) on the relationship between the writers Mihai Eminescu, Veronica Micle and Ion Creangă (all deceased at the time of the production), released by the Bucharest chapter of Pathé.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Early color motion picture processes such as Kinemacolor (known for the feature *With Our King and Queen Through India* (1912)) and Prizma Color (known for *Everywhere With Prizma* (1919) and the five-reel feature *Bali the Unknown* (1921)) used travelogues to promote the new color processes.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In contrast, Technicolor concentrated primarily on getting their process adopted by Hollywood studios for fiction feature films.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Also during this period, Frank Hurley's feature documentary film, *South* (1919) about the Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition was released.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The film documented the failed Antarctic expedition led by Ernest Shackleton in 1914.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Flaherty's *Nanook of the North* in 1922, documentary film embraced romanticism.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Flaherty filmed a number of heavily staged romantic documentary films during this time period, often showing how his subjects would have lived 100 years earlier and not how they lived right then.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] For instance, in *Nanook of the North*, Flaherty did not allow his subjects to shoot a walrus with a nearby shotgun, but had them use a harpoon instead.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Some of Flaherty's staging, such as building a roofless igloo for interior shots, was done to accommodate the filming technology of the time.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Paramount Pictures tried to repeat the success of Flaherty's *Nanook* and *Moana* with two romanticized documentaries, *Grass* (1925) and *Chang* (1927), both directed by Merian C.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The "*city symphony*" sub film genre consisted of avant-garde films during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] These films were particularly influenced by modern art, namely Cubism, Constructivism, and Impressionism.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] According to art historian and author Scott MacDonald, city symphony films can be described as, "An intersection between documentary and avant-garde film: an *avant-doc*"; however, A.L.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Rees suggests regarding them as avant-garde films.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Early titles produced within this genre include: *Manhatta* (New York; dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Paul Strand, 1921); *Rien que les heures/Nothing But The Hours* (France; dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Alberto Cavalcanti, 1926); *Twenty Four Dollar Island* (dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Mikhail Kaufman, 1927); *Études sur Paris* (dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] André Sauvage, 1928); *The Bridge* (1928) and *Rain* (1929), both by Joris Ivens; *São Paulo, Sinfonia da Metrópole* (dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Adalberto Kemeny, 1929), *Berlin: Symphony of a Metropolis* (dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Walter Ruttmann, 1927); *Man with a Movie Camera* (dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Dziga Vertov, 1929); *Douro, Faina Fluvial* (dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Manoel de Oliveira, 1931); and *Rhapsody in Two Languages* (dir.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] A city symphony film, as the name suggests, is most often based around a major metropolitan city area and seeks to capture the life, events and activities of the city.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] It can use abstract cinematography (Walter Ruttman's *Berlin*) or may use Soviet montage theory (Dziga Vertov's, *Man with a Movie Camera*).
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Most importantly, a city symphony film is a form of cinepoetry, shot and edited in the style of a "symphony".
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] These films tend to feature people as products of their environment, and lean towards the avant-garde.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Dziga Vertov was central to the Soviet *Kino-Pravda* (literally, "cinematic truth") newsreel series of the 1920s.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Vertov believed the camera – with its varied lenses, shot-counter shot editing, time-lapse, ability to slow motion, stop motion and fast-motion – could render reality more accurately than the human eye, and created a film philosophy from it.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The newsreel tradition is important in documentary film.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Newsreels at this time were sometimes staged but were usually re-enactments of events that had already happened, not attempts to steer events as they were in the process of happening.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] For instance, much of the battle footage from the early 20th century was staged; the cameramen would usually arrive on site after a major battle and re-enact scenes to film them.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The propagandist tradition consists of films made with the explicit purpose of persuading an audience of a point.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] One of the most celebrated and controversial propaganda films is Leni Riefenstahl's film *Triumph of the Will* (1935), which chronicled the 1934 Nazi Party Congress and was commissioned by Adolf Hitler.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Leftist filmmakers Joris Ivens and Henri Storck directed *Borinage* (1931) about the Belgian coal mining region.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Luis Buñuel directed a "surrealist" documentary *Las Hurdes* (1933).
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Pare Lorentz's *The Plow That Broke the Plains* (1936) and *The River* (1938) and Willard Van Dyke's *The City* (1939) are notable New Deal productions, each presenting complex combinations of social and ecological awareness, government propaganda, and leftist viewpoints.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Frank Capra's *Why We Fight* (1942–1944) series was a newsreel series in the United States, commissioned by the government to convince the U.S. public that it was time to go to war.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Constance Bennett and her husband Henri de la Falaise produced two feature-length documentaries, *Legong: Dance of the Virgins* (1935) filmed in Bali, and *Kilou the Killer Tiger* (1936) filmed in Indochina.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In Canada, the Film Board, set up by John Grierson, was set up for the same propaganda reasons.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] It also created newsreels that were seen by their national governments as legitimate counter-propaganda to the psychological warfare of Nazi Germany orchestrated by Joseph Goebbels.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In Britain, a number of different filmmakers came together under John Grierson.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] They became known as the Documentary Film Movement.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Grierson, Alberto Cavalcanti, Harry Watt, Basil Wright, and Humphrey Jennings amongst others succeeded in blending propaganda, information, and education with a more poetic aesthetic approach to documentary.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Examples of their work include *Drifters* (John Grierson), *Song of Ceylon* (Basil Wright), *Fires Were Started*, and *A Diary for Timothy* (Humphrey Jennings).
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Auden, composers such as Benjamin Britten, and writers such as J.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Among the best known films of the movement are *Night Mail* and *Coal Face*.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Cinéma vérité (or the closely related direct cinema) was dependent on some technical advances to exist: light, quiet and reliable cameras, and portable sync sound.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Cinéma vérité and similar documentary traditions can thus be seen, in a broader perspective, as a reaction against studio-based film production constraints.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Shooting on location, with smaller crews, would also happen in the French New Wave, the filmmakers taking advantage of advances in technology allowing smaller, handheld cameras and synchronized sound to film events on location as they unfolded.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The directors of the movement take different viewpoints on their degree of involvement with their subjects.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Kopple and Pennebaker, for instance, choose non-involvement (or at least no overt involvement), and Perrault, Rouch, Koenig, and Kroitor favor direct involvement or even provocation when they deem it necessary.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The films *Chronicle of a Summer* (Jean Rouch), *Dont Look Back* (D.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The fundamentals of the style include following a person during a crisis with a moving, often handheld, camera to capture more personal reactions.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] There are no sit-down interviews, and the shooting ratio (the amount of film shot to the finished product) is very high, often reaching 80 to one.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] From there, editors find and sculpt the work into a film.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The editors of the movement – such as Werner Nold, Charlotte Zwerin, Muffie Meyer, Susan Froemke, and Ellen Hovde – are often overlooked, but their input to the films was so vital that they were often given co-director credits.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Famous cinéma vérité/direct cinema films include *The Snowshoers (Les Raquetteurs)*, *Showman*, *Salesman*, *Near Death*, and *The Children Were Watching*.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In the 1960s and 1970s, documentary film was often regarded as a political weapon against neocolonialism and capitalism in general, especially in Latin America, but also in a changing society.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] *La Hora de los hornos* (*The Hour of the Furnaces*, from 1968), directed by Octavio Getino and Fernando Solanas, influenced a whole generation of filmmakers.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] A June 2020 article in *The New York Times* reviewed the political documentary *And She Could Be Next*, directed by Grace Lee and Marjan Safinia.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The *Times* described the documentary not only as focusing on women in politics, but more specifically on women of color, their communities, and the significant changes they have wrought upon America.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Box office analysts have noted that the documentary film genre has become increasingly successful in theatrical release with films such as *Fahrenheit 9/11*, *Super Size Me*, *Food, Inc.*, *Earth*, *March of the Penguins*, and *An Inconvenient Truth* among the most prominent examples.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Compared to dramatic narrative films, documentaries typically have far lower budgets which makes them attractive to film companies because even a limited theatrical release can be highly profitable.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The nature of documentary films has expanded in the past 30 years from the cinéma vérité style introduced in the 1960s in which the use of portable camera and sound equipment allowed an intimate relationship between filmmaker and subject.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The line blurs between documentary and narrative and some works are very personal, such as Marlon Riggs's *Tongues Untied* (1989) and *Black Is...Black Ain't* (1995), which mix expressive, poetic, and rhetorical elements and stresses subjectivities rather than historical materials.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Some films such as *The Thin Blue Line* by Errol Morris incorporate stylized re-enactments, and Michael Moore's *Roger & Me* place far more interpretive control with the director.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentary filmmakers are increasingly using social impact campaigns with their films.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Social impact campaigns seek to leverage media projects by converting public awareness of social issues and causes into engagement and action, largely by offering the audience a way to get involved.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Examples of such documentaries include *Kony 2012*, *Salam Neighbor, Gasland*, *Living on One Dollar*, and *Girl Rising*.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Although documentaries are financially more viable with the increasing popularity of the genre and the advent of the DVD, funding for documentary film production remains elusive.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Within the past decade, the largest exhibition opportunities have emerged from within the broadcast market, making filmmakers beholden to the tastes and influences of the broadcasters who have become their largest funding source.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Modern documentaries have some overlap with television forms, with the development of "reality television" that occasionally verges on the documentary but more often veers to the fictional or staged.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The "making-of" documentary shows how a movie or a computer game was produced.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Usually made for promotional purposes, it is closer to an advertisement than a classic documentary.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Modern lightweight digital video cameras and computer-based editing have greatly aided documentary makers, as has the dramatic drop in equipment prices.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The first film to take full advantage of this change was Martin Kunert and Eric Manes' *Voices of Iraq*, where 150 DV cameras were sent to Iraq during the war and passed out to Iraqis to record themselves.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Films in the documentary form without words have been made.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] *Listen to Britain*, directed by Humphrey Jennings and Stuart McAllister in 1942, is a wordless meditation on wartime Britain.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] From 1982, the Qatsi trilogy and the similar *Baraka* could be described as visual tone poems, with music related to the images, but no spoken content.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] *Koyaanisqatsi* (part of the Qatsi trilogy) consists primarily of slow motion and time-lapse photography of cities and many natural landscapes across the United States.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] *Baraka* tries to capture the great pulse of humanity as it flocks and swarms in daily activity and religious ceremonies.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The 2004 film *Genesis* shows animal and plant life in states of expansion, decay, sex, and death, with some, but little, narration.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The traditional style for narration is to have a dedicated narrator read a script which is dubbed onto the audio track.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The narrator never appears on camera and may not necessarily have knowledge of the subject matter or involvement in the writing of the script.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] This style of narration uses title screens to visually narrate the documentary.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The screens are held for about 5–10 seconds to allow adequate time for the viewer to read them.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] They are similar to the ones shown at the end of movies based on true stories, but they are shown throughout, typically between scenes.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In this style, there is a host who appears on camera, conducts interviews, and who also does voice-overs.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The release of *The Thin Blue Line* (1988) directed by Errol Morris introduced possibilities for emerging forms of the hybrid documentary.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Indeed, it was disqualified for an Academy Award because of the stylized recreations.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Traditional documentary filmmaking typically removes signs of fictionalization to distinguish itself from fictional film genres.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Audiences have recently become more distrustful of the media's traditional fact production, making them more receptive to experimental ways of telling facts.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The hybrid documentary implements truth games to challenge traditional fact production.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Although it is fact-based, the hybrid documentary is not explicit about what should be understood, creating an open dialogue between subject and audience.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Clio Barnard's *The Arbor* (2010), Joshua Oppenheimer's *The Act of Killing* (2012), Mads Brügger's *The Ambassador*, and Alma Har'el's *Bombay Beach* (2011) are a few notable examples.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Docufiction is a hybrid genre from two basic ones, fiction film and documentary, practiced since the first documentary films were made.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Fake-fiction is a genre which deliberately presents real, unscripted events in the form of a fiction film, making them appear as staged.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] This form of documentary release is becoming more popular and accepted as costs and difficulty with finding TV or theatrical release slots increases.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] It is also commonly used for more "specialist" documentaries, which might not have general interest to a wider TV audience.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Examples are military, cultural arts, transport, sports, animals, etc.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Compilation films were pioneered in 1927 by Esfir Schub with *The Fall of the Romanov Dynasty*.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] More recent examples include *Point of Order!* (1964), directed by Emile de Antonio about the McCarthy hearings.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Similarly, *The Last Cigarette* combines the testimony of various tobacco company executives before the U.S.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Congress with archival propaganda extolling the virtues of smoking.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Poetic documentaries, which first appeared in the 1920s, were a sort of reaction against both the content and the rapidly crystallizing grammar of the early fiction film.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The poetic mode moved away from continuity editing and instead organized images of the material world by means of associations and patterns, both in terms of time and space.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Well-rounded characters – "lifelike people" – were absent; instead, people appeared in these films as entities, just like any other, that are found in the material world.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The films were fragmentary, impressionistic, lyrical.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Their disruption of the coherence of time and space – a coherence favored by the fiction films of the day – can also be seen as an element of the modernist counter-model of cinematic narrative.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The "real world" – Nichols calls it the "historical world" – was broken up into fragments and aesthetically reconstituted using film form.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Expository documentaries speak directly to the viewer, often in the form of an authoritative commentary employing voiceover or titles, proposing a strong argument and point of view.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] These films are rhetorical, and try to persuade the viewer.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] (They may use a rich and sonorous male voice.) The (voice-of-God) commentary often sounds "objective" and omniscient.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Images are often not paramount; they exist to advance the argument.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The rhetoric insistently presses upon us to read the images in a certain fashion.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Historical documentaries in this mode deliver an unproblematic and "objective" account and interpretation of past events.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Observational documentaries attempt to spontaneously observe their subjects with minimal intervention.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Filmmakers who worked in this subgenre often saw the poetic mode as too abstract and the expository mode as too didactic.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The first observational docs date back to the 1960s; the technological developments which made them possible include mobile lightweight cameras and portable sound recording equipment for synchronized sound.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Often, this mode of film eschewed voice-over commentary, post-synchronized dialogue and music, or re-enactments.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The films aimed for immediacy, intimacy, and revelation of individual human character in ordinary life situations.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentaries are shown in schools around the world in order to educate students.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Used to introduce various topics to children, they are often used with a school lesson or shown many times to reinforce an idea.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] There are several challenges associated with translation of documentaries.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The main two are working conditions and problems with terminology.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentary translators very often have to meet tight deadlines.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Normally, the translator has between five and seven days to hand over the translation of a 90-minute programme.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Another problem is the lack of postproduction script or the poor quality of the transcription.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] A correct transcription is essential for a translator to do their work properly, however many times the script is not even given to the translator, which is a major impediment since documentaries are characterised by "the abundance of terminological units and very specific proper names".
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Such mistakes in proper names are for instance: "Jungle Reinhard instead of Django Reinhart, Jorn Asten instead of Jane Austen, and Magnus Axle instead of Aldous Huxley".
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] The process of translation of a documentary programme requires working with very specific, often scientific terminology.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Documentary translators are not usually specialists in a given field.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Therefore, they are compelled to undertake extensive research whenever asked to make a translation of a specific documentary programme in order to understand it correctly and deliver the final product free of mistakes and inaccuracies.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] Additionally, translators of minorised languages often have to face another problem: some terms may not even exist in the target language.
[src:documentary-film/documentary-film] In such cases, they have to create new terminology or consult specialists to find proper solutions.
